So Gotham is optimized for military and defense 
use cases and intel as well. I would say they both  

366
00:30:15,920 --> 00:30:22,720
have some things in common. So they both have, 
I would describe this almost as a pyramid where  

367
00:30:22,720 --> 00:30:26,960
the bottom layer is data ingestion, the middle 
layer is data mapping, and then the top layer is  

368
00:30:26,960 --> 00:30:32,080
anything that's user facing. So any UI component. 
And then if you think of Foundry for a second,  

369
00:30:33,200 --> 00:30:37,280
there's different tools that allow you to 
ingest data to it. There's different tools  

370
00:30:37,280 --> 00:30:42,320
that allow you to easily build data pipelines 
and clean up data, which everybody has to do.  

371
00:30:42,320 --> 00:30:46,880
And then there's a bunch of tooling that 
allows you to build compelling UIs on top,  

372
00:30:46,880 --> 00:30:53,120
do point and click analytics, do notebook style 
workflows, however technical you are. So that's,  

373
00:30:53,120 --> 00:30:59,200
I mean, when it's a platform, it's a suite 
of things that has a common data backing but  

374
00:30:59,200 --> 00:31:04,000
contains a bunch of different applications.So I 
think that is somewhat true of Gotham as well. But  

375
00:31:04,560 --> 00:31:09,920
when you log in, you see this unified interface.
So what is the actual difference then? I would  

376
00:31:09,920 --> 00:31:15,600
say with Gotham, you're looking much more at 
workflows like that involve maps, for example.  

377
00:31:15,600 --> 00:31:19,840
So when you're doing a military operation, a lot 
of the time you are going to be looking at a map  

378
00:31:19,840 --> 00:31:26,640
and you are going to be monitoring the movement 
of troops or tanks or whatever it is. Another big  

379
00:31:26,640 --> 00:31:36,160
difference is the idea of graph-based analysis. So 
Gotham, one of the use cases was finding combing  

380
00:31:36,160 --> 00:31:41,600
through networks of terrorists and basically 
finding the bad guys. So being able to do  

381
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:47,200
queries that are graph-based was important. So 
it's like, "Who is everybody that Lenny called  

382
00:31:47,200 --> 00:31:51,680
in the last week?" Imagine all the nodes fanning 
out from there. And then it's like, "Okay. Well,  

383
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:55,680
this one looks interesting. Let's zoom in 
on that. What is this person's location?" 

384
00:31:56,320 --> 00:32:01,520
So it's this very graph-based way of thinking that 
also applies to things like fraud. So Gotham has  

385
00:32:01,520 --> 00:32:06,480
been deployed against fraud, but if you look 
at Foundry, it doesn't actually emphasize that  

386
00:32:06,480 --> 00:32:11,120
component so much because it turns out, let's 
say you're a B2B SaaS company, you're probably  

387
00:32:11,120 --> 00:32:15,200
not doing that much graph-based analysis. 
You're doing things that look a lot more like  

388
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:20,720
classic SQL queries, tables, that kind of stuff. 
So Foundry is a lot more traditional in that way.

389
00:32:20,720 --> 00:32:25,120
That was an amazing explanation. For the first 
time, I am starting to understand what these  

390
00:32:25,120 --> 00:32:29,920
products do. Basically, it's just sucks in a 
bunch of data, cleans it up so you can actually  

391
00:32:29,920 --> 00:32:35,920
trust it and then helps you interact with it 
in various use cases, maps, graphs, tables.

392
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:36,320
Yes.

393
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:40,560
Okay. Amazing. The example you gave 
of what you worked on at Airbus,  

394
00:32:40,560 --> 00:32:44,720
you described it as basically a sauna 
for making planes. Is that right?

395
00:32:44,720 --> 00:32:45,120
Yes.

396
00:32:45,760 --> 00:32:50,320
So how much of that does becomes a part of 
this core product versus stays this one-off  

397
00:32:50,320 --> 00:32:55,680
thing? Is it elements, that's a cool innovation, 
let's put that into Foundry. How does that work?

398
00:32:55,680 --> 00:33:01,680
This was a really interesting story actually. So 
the initial problem that we came into with Airbus  

399
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:06,160
was that they had a new aircraft called 
the A350 beautiful aircraft. By the way,  

400
00:33:06,160 --> 00:33:11,440
if you get to, I think if you fly New York 
to Singapore, it's often in that A350. Really  

401
00:33:11,440 --> 00:33:16,400
nice. So it was a relatively new aircraft 
at the time, and their mandate to us was,  

402
00:33:16,400 --> 00:33:19,600
"Okay. We need to ramp up production 
of this really fast," much faster than  

403
00:33:19,600 --> 00:33:23,520
we've ever done it before. So it's like the 
numbers are very approximate, but it's like,  

404
00:33:23,520 --> 00:33:27,600
"Okay. We're producing 4 this month, we need 
to do 8 the next month, 16 the month after,  

405
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:31,280
and so forth, and you are going to help us do 
it." So this goes back to what I was saying  

406
00:33:31,280 --> 00:33:35,360
earlier is the mandate wasn't like, "Hey, we need 
to upgrade our data infrastructure. We thought you  

407
00:33:35,360 --> 00:33:39,920
guys would be met the list of requirements." 
It was much more just like, "Please help us  

408
00:33:39,920 --> 00:33:46,400
accomplish this mission. This is the big thing."
So we went in, scoped out the problem. There  

409
00:33:46,400 --> 00:33:50,240
were a bunch of different things that we 
could build that helped accelerate this,  

410
00:33:50,240 --> 00:33:54,960
but one of the basic problems that we figured out 
was that without getting too much into the weeds,  

411
00:33:54,960 --> 00:33:59,680
the way the factory would work, is that there's a 
bunch of stations and you can think of the plane  

412
00:33:59,680 --> 00:34:03,920
as literally moving between each station and 
then each station would do a certain set of  

413
00:34:03,920 --> 00:34:09,520
work on it. So initially, it's literally a big 
fuselage and the fuselage is sitting there and  

414
00:34:09,520 --> 00:34:13,760
then people are doing a bunch of work orders 
against it. They need parts in order to do  

415
00:34:13,760 --> 00:34:18,640
that work. And then at some point they say, 
"Okay. This is ready to move to Station 31,  

416
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:23,200
and the plane is physically moved to the next 
station and then Station 31 does its next thing." 

417
00:34:23,200 --> 00:34:27,280
So in order for the next station to do its work 
properly, they need to know, one, what work was  

418
00:34:27,280 --> 00:34:30,960
done at the previous station and what work is 
remaining? Two is just like, if you think about  

419
00:34:30,960 --> 00:34:38,720
this problem, not all work is going to get done 
on time. So things carry over to the next team,  

420
00:34:38,720 --> 00:34:44,960
and the next team then has to... So when I'm 
describing this problem to you can start to  

421
00:34:44,960 --> 00:34:50,080
visualize, okay, maybe I need some Gantt chart to 
this, and I need the ability to click in and say,  

422
00:34:50,080 --> 00:34:55,600
"Okay. What did Station 30 do and what work 
orders remained undone?" And then it's like,  

423
00:34:55,600 --> 00:34:58,960
"Okay. For those work orders, what parts do 
I need and where in the factory might they  

424
00:34:59,520 --> 00:35:06,160
be?" So this was very, very hard to do as it is. 
A lot of it was just relying on people going and  

425
00:35:06,160 --> 00:35:11,360
having conversations with other people on the 
factory floor, and coming from tech where it's  

426
00:35:11,360 --> 00:35:15,120
maybe not as complicated as building aircraft, 
that is a phenomenally complicated process,  

427
00:35:15,120 --> 00:35:18,960
but it is easy to see, okay, you can 
actually improve this problem with software. 

428
00:35:20,960 --> 00:35:26,800
All that data was stored in SAP and SAP is like 
established software. It's good at what it does,  

429
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:31,120
but it's not the most user-friendly necessarily, 
especially if you're not an expert in how it  

430
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:36,080
stores data. The table names are very hard to 
understand and read. So one of the things we  

431
00:35:36,080 --> 00:35:40,480
figured out was just if you can pull in 
these tables that may as well be written  

432
00:35:40,480 --> 00:35:46,400
in completely alien language, the table name 
would just be like S3, F1_Z or something like  

433
00:35:46,400 --> 00:35:51,280
that. And you'd have to know, okay, this is the 
table where the part ID is stored or something. 

434
00:35:51,280 --> 00:35:55,920
If you could pull in those tables and join them 
in the right ways, and then just map them to human  

435
00:35:55,920 --> 00:36:01,920
concepts that humans can understand, so things 
like a part a work order, an aircraft, et cetera,  

436
00:36:01,920 --> 00:36:06,960
and basically build a hierarchy or mapping between 
them, then what you can do is, a user can just  

437
00:36:06,960 --> 00:36:11,920
log in and say, "Okay. Aircraft 79, where is 
that? Okay. It's at Station 31. All right.  

438
00:36:11,920 --> 00:36:16,400
These are the work orders, et cetera." So you've 
translated it into a more human-legible thing. 

439
00:36:16,400 --> 00:36:22,400
So the thing we built, I slightly flippantly 
described it as Asana. It's a little different.  

440
00:36:22,400 --> 00:36:26,240
But basically that's what it did, was it gave 
you a unified view of, okay, this is what's  

441
00:36:26,240 --> 00:36:30,000
going on inside the factory. This is the work 
that needs to be done on this particular plane.  

442
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:36,560
And then me today going to my job at Station 31, 
what work orders do I need to fulfill and where  

443
00:36:36,560 --> 00:36:42,560
are the parts that I need to do that? So did this 
directly become a part of Foundry? Not exactly,  

444
00:36:42,560 --> 00:36:48,080
because the way that other companies work is 
not going to be using this same set of concepts,  

445
00:36:48,080 --> 00:36:55,680
but the overall idea of taking a bunch 
of tables, and then mapping them to human  

446
00:36:55,680 --> 00:37:00,720
understandable concepts was a very powerful one.
So this actually resulted in a big piece of  

447
00:37:00,720 --> 00:37:05,920
Foundry now, which they call Ontology. You've 
probably heard this term as you've seen... If you  

448
00:37:05,920 --> 00:37:10,160
see Palantir presentations, they always talk about 
Ontology. This is what they actually mean by that,  

449
00:37:10,160 --> 00:37:15,520
is it is a set of concepts that is understandable 
to you as a human and you are not having to go and  

450
00:37:15,520 --> 00:37:21,920
dig around and do. You're just able to say, "Where 
is the aircraft now and where is it going next?"  

451
00:37:22,640 --> 00:37:29,280
So the ontology became a huge piece of Foundry. 
It was directly informed by the learnings that we  

452
00:37:29,280 --> 00:37:34,640
had from building that application inside that 
factory. And I would say it's still a very big  

453
00:37:34,640 --> 00:37:41,360
differentiator today. I don't think too many 
other companies ship this kind of stuff yet.

454
00:37:41,360 --> 00:37:45,600
Wow. I love how excited you still are about 
this. I could see it being so fulfilling to  

455
00:37:45,600 --> 00:37:52,000
solve this big problem. I saw a stat that I think, 
4X their productivity. What was the number there?

456
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:55,920
Yeah. I don't recall the exact 
stat, but we did ramp up production,  

457
00:37:55,920 --> 00:37:59,040
I think at least 4X that 1 
year, which I mean obviously,  

458
00:37:59,040 --> 00:38:04,400
they did this and we just helped with it. But 
that CEO said that we played a critical part.

459
00:38:05,040 --> 00:38:06,800
Also, you moved to France, I think for this. That  

