01:00:43,040 --> 01:00:47,120
I'm really going to, I'm work this evening if 
that's what it takes to get this thing working,  

731
01:00:47,120 --> 01:00:51,600
and I'm not just going to check my boxes, I'm 
actually going to look towards what is the real  

732
01:00:51,600 --> 01:00:56,080
outcome that this business is trying to achieve." 
And everything I'm saying feels kind of obvious,  

733
01:00:56,080 --> 01:00:59,520
but when you actually feel that difference 
between somebody who's just checking the boxes  

734
01:00:59,520 --> 01:01:03,840
and somebody who's kind of an animal in this way, 
they'll actually go and pursue and accomplish the  

735
01:01:03,840 --> 01:01:08,800
end outcome, that difference is very, very 
big and it matters so much for your first 20  

736
01:01:08,800 --> 01:01:14,000
people. And there's no science to finding these 
people. It's not like you can just put somebody  

737
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:17,920
who cares about outcomes in your JD and then 
suddenly you'll get all these people applying. 

738
01:01:18,640 --> 01:01:22,720
So then it's like, okay, well how do you 
screen for that and how do you find those  

739
01:01:22,720 --> 01:01:27,760
types of people? And so that's where it gets 
really interesting. I think that's where the  

740
01:01:27,760 --> 01:01:33,840
mission alignment comes in, and so you do have 
to find people who, for what you are doing,  

741
01:01:33,840 --> 01:01:40,880
have this extra maybe private reason to care about 
it a little bit more than the average person.  

742
01:01:40,880 --> 01:01:45,760
So I think for Palantir, they did hire a 
lot of vets, for example, or maybe people  

743
01:01:45,760 --> 01:01:50,640
who were a little bit more patriotic or 
pro-America than the average tech employee,  

744
01:01:50,640 --> 01:01:56,880
and those people had an extra reason to Palantir 
and an extra reason to try that little bit harder.  

745
01:01:56,880 --> 01:02:03,760
And so what I'm doing is a little bit more in the 
kind of medical and health space, and so I think  

746
01:02:03,760 --> 01:02:10,080
people who have themselves had experiences 
with this system have maybe had relatives  

747
01:02:10,880 --> 01:02:15,600
go through difficult experiences with things 
like cancer or whatever it is. They're just  

748
01:02:15,600 --> 01:02:20,160
that extra bit motivated to really care about 
the thing you're trying to do and then work that  

749
01:02:20,160 --> 01:02:25,200
little bit harder, and so I think aggressively 
filtering early on to things like mission fit,  

750
01:02:25,200 --> 01:02:28,480
how much have you cared about stuff 
in the past, and what's an example. 

751
01:02:28,480 --> 01:02:32,800
You ask questions like, what's the hardest you've 
ever worked to get something done and why? And  

752
01:02:32,800 --> 01:02:38,080
that does differentiate a lot of people, a lot of 
people don't actually have a great answer to that.  

753
01:02:38,080 --> 01:02:43,120
So I would say that's been a really big learning, 
is it's less about testing for the right skills,  

754
01:02:43,120 --> 01:02:47,680
yes, that's important, two it's much 
more about just who has that extra 20%.

755
01:02:47,680 --> 01:02:52,560
That is really interesting, everything you've 
shared is essentially around motivation, and  

756
01:02:52,560 --> 01:02:59,760
drive, and passion, and kind of just commitment 
to working on this intently, and it's almost like  

757
01:02:59,760 --> 01:03:04,400
a second thought of just like, oh, also they're 
really smart and skilled at stuff. It feels like  

758
01:03:04,400 --> 01:03:08,080
that's just table stakes and this is actually 
what makes the difference in your experience.

759
01:03:08,080 --> 01:03:12,000
Yeah, I totally agree, and I think it's different 
for every business. So I think if you're in a  

760
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:16,400
space like B2B SaaS where maybe it's a little 
harder to tell the story of like, oh, this is  

761
01:03:16,400 --> 01:03:21,360
so mission-critical, whatever, there are other 
ways of getting at this thing. So for example, I  

762
01:03:21,360 --> 01:03:25,680
know a lot of people, again, it's a little played 
out now, but I know a lot of people who for sales  

763
01:03:25,680 --> 01:03:31,360
teams, they will explicitly go for people who were 
professional athletes or played sports in college,  

764
01:03:31,360 --> 01:03:34,560
and it's like, okay, what does that test for? 
It's like you are very, very disciplined,  

765
01:03:34,560 --> 01:03:38,320
you're very, very goals and numbers oriented 
and you're willing to just work really,  

766
01:03:38,320 --> 01:03:43,120
really hard. And so there's all these kind 
of lateral ways of getting at these qualities  

767
01:03:43,120 --> 01:03:49,520
that I think you just have to be intentional 
about as a founder. As a personal example,  

768
01:03:49,520 --> 01:03:55,120
I'm a runner and so I actually love meeting fellow 
runners and I kind of joke like, "Oh, maybe I'll  

769
01:03:55,120 --> 01:04:00,720
go higher from run clubs or something like that."
But it's just same with I play a lot of chess,  

770
01:04:00,720 --> 01:04:04,640
I love meeting chess players. I'm not necessarily 
saying that's the right kind of hire for me,  

771
01:04:04,640 --> 01:04:11,200
but I think having this thing of here 
are some traits that seem uncorrelated,  

772
01:04:11,200 --> 01:04:16,640
but which actually give you good signal to this 
person's personality, those are actually really  

773
01:04:16,640 --> 01:04:22,160
important. The last thing I'll say just as a 
funny illustration of that concept is I think Max  

774
01:04:22,160 --> 01:04:27,360
Levchin tells the story of somebody interviewing 
at PayPal early on and he passed all the skill  

775
01:04:27,360 --> 01:04:32,080
interviews and then it just got to the final round 
and he said something about liking to shoot hoops,  

776
01:04:32,080 --> 01:04:40,160
like he liked to play basketball, and they 
were like instant reject. The vibe here was  

777
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:46,560
like if you're not a mega Linux nerd, hardcore 
computer person, then we don't want you here,  

778
01:04:46,560 --> 01:04:49,680
even if you actually passed all the tests just 
because you like to shoot hoops. Now whether that  

779
01:04:49,680 --> 01:04:54,480
was the right call or the wrong call, don't know, 
but that's an example of what I'm talking about.

780
01:04:54,480 --> 01:05:00,640
I think that's a great echo back. People hearing 
this may be like, "What the hell? How dare they  

781
01:05:00,640 --> 01:05:06,480
do that?" But this is exactly what you said at 
the beginning of our conversation, that like an  

782
01:05:06,480 --> 01:05:11,280
approach to building a generational business is 
to be very clear about who this is not for, and  

783
01:05:11,280 --> 01:05:15,520
that's okay, it's your company, not everyone needs 
to work there. And it's almost saving them time  

784
01:05:15,520 --> 01:05:20,720
because they might realize this isn't for me, this 
isn't the people I want to be around necessarily.  

785
01:05:20,720 --> 01:05:25,600
So I think it's important to see that side of 
it, is it's your business, it's important to  

786
01:05:25,600 --> 01:05:31,680
be clear about who is a good fit for the company 
and who's not. Speaking of that, let's talk about  

787
01:05:31,680 --> 01:05:39,200
product management for a bit. I know Palantir 
PMs are not traditional product managers. I  

788
01:05:39,200 --> 01:05:45,760
imagine people have the title, Product Manager at 
Palantir, okay, so if so, as far as you understand  

789
01:05:45,760 --> 01:05:50,720
what's the difference between say a PM at Palantir 
versus a traditional PM say at a FANG company?

790
01:05:50,720 --> 01:05:55,360
Palantir was, as far as I remember, quite 
anti-PM for a while and eventually we did  

791
01:05:55,360 --> 01:05:57,840
need them because we just got more 
serious about product testing.

792
01:05:57,840 --> 01:05:59,600
Classic story, classic story.

793
01:05:59,600 --> 01:06:00,240
A classic story.

794
01:06:00,240 --> 01:06:01,520
In many companies,

795
01:06:01,520 --> 01:06:07,040
The big difference or one big difference I 
noticed was that they were extremely careful  

796
01:06:07,040 --> 01:06:14,720
about only making people PMs who had first proven 
themselves out as forward deploying engineers. You  

797
01:06:14,720 --> 01:06:22,800
basically could not become a PM any other way. 
So as an example, when I mentioned earlier the  

798
01:06:22,800 --> 01:06:26,800
thing that we built for the plane factory, 
the person who was managing that deployment,  

799
01:06:26,800 --> 01:06:31,920
she later became the PM for ontology, and it 
was just because she'd kind of proven her method  

800
01:06:31,920 --> 01:06:37,120
in the field. And the reason for that's pretty 
simple, it's going to be someone who understand  

801
01:06:37,120 --> 01:06:42,560
how customers work and has that customer empathy, 
and it's going to be someone who has this drive  

802
01:06:42,560 --> 01:06:47,520
to get things done because that's what BD selected 
for. I think the failure mode that they were very,  

803
01:06:47,520 --> 01:06:54,560
very averse to in traditional PMs was this 
kind of Google Docs syndrome of like, okay,  

804
01:06:54,560 --> 01:06:58,560
I'm going to write my product requirement 
documents, and I'm going to manage it in  

805
01:06:58,560 --> 01:07:03,920
this very sort of sane, rational way I think, 
so the company was really rigorous about that. 

806
01:07:03,920 --> 01:07:09,200
And so basically PMs were almost always 
internal promotions and they always came from  

807
01:07:09,920 --> 01:07:15,440
BD. I am not aware of a single case where we took 
somebody who was a PM at a place like Google,  

808
01:07:15,440 --> 01:07:19,520
which produces many excellent PMs and hired 
them successfully into Palantir, it's just  

809
01:07:19,520 --> 01:07:25,440
a very different vibe. So I think that was one 
thing. This is maybe more of a classic PM trait,  

810
01:07:25,440 --> 01:07:30,960
but you just had to be either an engineer yourself 
or extremely good at working with engineers, and  

811
01:07:30,960 --> 01:07:37,520
the ones I saw who succeeded the most were just 
best friends with their engineering team. And the  

812
01:07:37,520 --> 01:07:42,160
team would always just be like one, it was called 
the group pm and then it would be a lot of very,  

813
01:07:42,160 --> 01:07:47,600
very good engineers. And basically the success 
or failure mode was just do the engineers and  

814
01:07:47,600 --> 01:07:54,000
trust you? I mentioned before Palantir how is 
very almost disagreeable personalities, and so  

815
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:58,640
if you didn't gain the trust of engineering 
team pretty fast, you didn't last very long.

816
01:07:58,640 --> 01:08:04,080
I think we've cracked the question of why are 
Palantir PM's so successful? First of all,  

817
01:08:04,080 --> 01:08:09,600
the hiring bar is just basically hiring for 
leaders in a lot of different ways, to this,  

818
01:08:09,600 --> 01:08:14,400
I don't know, forge for founders where they're 
working with a company solving a real problem,  

819
01:08:14,400 --> 01:08:18,640
building a real product that makes money, and 
then those are the people that become the PMs  

820
01:08:18,640 --> 01:08:23,440
at Palantir and then they go on to leave and 
that's why 30% of them end up starting companies,  

821
01:08:23,440 --> 01:08:28,880
I'm surprised it's not higher, or become first 
PMs at other companies or heads of product.

822
01:08:28,880 --> 01:08:33,760
Yeah, absolutely, it's crazy. I was part 
of a pretty small team within Palantir,  

823
01:08:33,760 --> 01:08:39,680
I think it was 20 to 25 people when I joined, 
and I think at least six of them now are either  

824
01:08:39,680 --> 01:08:45,520
unicorn or just pre-unicorn founders from that 
group of 25 people, which is actually a crazy  

825
01:08:45,520 --> 01:08:49,360
ratio. And then a bunch more have become 
founders recently at an earlier stage,  

826
01:08:49,360 --> 01:08:54,480
so yeah, there's all these little pockets of 
excellence and it's been really interesting to  

827
01:08:54,480 --> 01:08:59,120
see. I think the other thing that's driving that 
a little bit is when you leave, it's just such  

828
01:08:59,120 --> 01:09:03,920
an interesting company to work at that I think 
the retention numbers were actually very high  

829
01:09:03,920 --> 01:09:10,800
for that company. People would often stay a lot 
longer than maybe the average Valley tenure. And  

830
01:09:10,800 --> 01:09:16,560
so when you left, it was really this decision of 
just something very specific is pulling you and  

831
01:09:16,560 --> 01:09:21,360
you want to kind of play the next level of the 
game, and so it was very unusual for someone to  

832
01:09:21,360 --> 01:09:26,480
leave and then join maybe a more traditional tech 
company. It's sort of like you're either going to  

833
01:09:26,480 --> 01:09:30,480
go become a founder or why would you leave when 
there's so many interesting different things to  

834
01:09:30,480 --> 01:09:35,040
work on? And I know that sounds a little 
culty, but that's what everyone thinks.

835
01:09:35,040 --> 01:09:38,640
I could totally see that. A lot of people 
that left Airbnb have never found something  

836
01:09:38,640 --> 01:09:43,360
more meaningful, it's just hard, especially if 
you're early. There's a stat that I didn't share  

837
01:09:43,360 --> 01:09:48,000
that I think is really interesting, and when you 
look at YC founders and where they've come from,  

838
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:53,520
I think you maybe shared in your post that 
there's more YC ex-Palantir founders than  

839
01:09:53,520 --> 01:10:00,480
there are ex-Google founders in spite of Google 
being something like 50 times bigger sample size.

840
01:10:00,480 --> 01:10:02,160
Yeah, yeah.

841
01:10:02,160 --> 01:10:07,840
Let's talk about the moral question of Palantir. 
A lot of people probably seeing the title of  

842
01:10:07,840 --> 01:10:13,840
this episode, hearing this, will not be excited 
about Palantir being highlighted and promoted,  

843
01:10:13,840 --> 01:10:17,440
a lot of people kind of disagree with 
what Palantir's doing. Builds products  

844
01:10:17,440 --> 01:10:21,680
that kill people in some ways, they work 
with governments they don't agree with. I  

845
01:10:21,680 --> 01:10:26,640
know you wrote a really insightful way 
of how you approach this question when  

846
01:10:26,640 --> 01:10:29,840
you decided to work at Palantir and how 
you see people tackle with this, can you  

847
01:10:29,840 --> 01:10:34,160
just talk about the framework that you landed 
on and how you thought about this yourself?

848
01:10:34,160 --> 01:10:38,960
Yeah, it's a really interesting topic, it's 
definitely very nuanced. I think what I was  

849
01:10:38,960 --> 01:10:45,600
trying to say in that post was a couple of things. 
One was that there was a lot of upside there. So  

850
01:10:45,600 --> 01:10:53,840
I worked on the US Covid response, I have friends 
who worked on Operation Warp Speed, and these are  

851
01:10:53,840 --> 01:10:59,200
all things that I think saved a lot of lives, and 
I was pretty focused while I was working at NIH on  

852
01:10:59,200 --> 01:11:03,280
cancer research. And so to me, these were just 
obviously good things and you couldn't do them  

853
01:11:03,280 --> 01:11:09,520
anywhere else, and so that was alone a reason 
to stay. The question I had in that post was,  

854
01:11:09,520 --> 01:11:13,120
well, okay, there are definitely going to 
be other pieces of this that people object  

855
01:11:13,120 --> 01:11:20,320
to. So during the 2016 to 2020 era, it became a 
pretty common thing to go into work in New York  

856
01:11:20,320 --> 01:11:26,880
and you'd have people protesting outside your 
office or doing all kinds of things. And so  

857
01:11:26,880 --> 01:11:30,880
there was this question of, well, is this okay? 
And I think the point I was trying to make was  

858
01:11:31,920 --> 01:11:38,000
it's rare that disengagement is the correct 
answer, and I think it's more recognized now,  

859
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:44,400
but especially then it went a bit too far.
So the famous example here is Google kind  

860
01:11:44,400 --> 01:11:50,880
of disengaging with a Pentagon AI project just 
because some people felt that working with the  

861
01:11:50,880 --> 01:11:56,880
Pentagon was itself morally bad. I think that's 
a way to sort of the left of what the median  

862
01:11:56,880 --> 01:12:01,520
American would say, I think the median American 
would say it's fine to work on defense stuff  

863
01:12:02,080 --> 01:12:07,680
within reason and assuming you're doing largely 
good things, and so there was just this kind of  

864
01:12:07,680 --> 01:12:12,560
almost arbitrage there at some point of just hang 
on, it's not like working on defense is inherently  

865
01:12:12,560 --> 01:12:17,920
evil, it's actually a pretty interesting thing. 
And then there's this question of, well, would  

866
01:12:17,920 --> 01:12:25,040
you rather be in the room and making this better 
or not? And so I'm struggling with how much I can  

867
01:12:25,040 --> 01:12:30,160
share here, but as a simple example, if you're 
doing even a workflow, which I think many people  

868
01:12:30,160 --> 01:12:36,400
would not be super comfortable with, let's say 
you're targeting somebody for some kind of strike.  

869
01:12:36,400 --> 01:12:40,960
If you compare the way it's done now to maybe 
the way it was done in 2010, it's going to be  

870
01:12:40,960 --> 01:12:44,800
a lot more targeted, it's going to be a lot more 
accurate, and so you've actually improved that  

871
01:12:44,800 --> 01:12:49,840
process and reduced the chance of error. Maybe 
you should feel good about that, right? Now, that  

872
01:12:49,840 --> 01:12:55,040
is a bullet many people are not willing to bite.
I didn't work on the defense side of the company  

873
01:12:55,040 --> 01:13:01,520
myself, but I think you have to be okay with 
these kinds of grade zones and actually actively  

874
01:13:01,520 --> 01:13:07,280
thinking about what you are doing. And that 
doesn't mean that it's always the right thing  

875
01:13:07,280 --> 01:13:13,760
to do to work in a defense company. Maybe we 
go into a very dark future and we start being  

876
01:13:13,760 --> 01:13:19,280
the bad guys in some ways, and then it's probably 
not a great idea to work at a defense company. So  

877
01:13:19,280 --> 01:13:25,600
it's a shifting landscape but I kind of felt 
pretty strongly that a lot of people in tech  

878
01:13:25,600 --> 01:13:33,120
just didn't want to think about this at all.
So you have engineers now who are working on  

879
01:13:33,120 --> 01:13:38,160
optimizing short form videos for higher 
engagement, and you sort of want to say  

880
01:13:38,160 --> 01:13:42,400
to them like, "Hey, are you thinking about what 
this is doing to the brains of young children?"  

881
01:13:42,400 --> 01:13:46,880
Or "Have you seen an 11-year-old kind of scrolling 
something for five hours and do you think this is  

882
01:13:46,880 --> 01:13:50,560
a good thing?" And I think people don't want to 
think about this stuff too much. I'm not saying  

883
01:13:50,560 --> 01:13:57,600
I know the answer, but there was almost this 
refusal to look at what tech was doing from a  

884
01:13:57,600 --> 01:14:03,520
political lens for a very long time. It was just 
like, "Hey, let us play with our toys, let us sit  

885
01:14:03,520 --> 01:14:08,400
in our little park, and don't bother us, and we're 
just going to build cool stuff and launch it." 

886
01:14:08,400 --> 01:14:15,280
And 2025, we're in a very, very different state 
of the world, tech is involved in politics now,  

887
01:14:15,280 --> 01:14:20,320
and politics basically came to tech. There's this 
famous image of Mark Zuckerberg, he's sitting in  

888
01:14:20,320 --> 01:14:25,680
Congress and he kind of looks very pale, and he's 
like, "Why have they dragged me in here again?"  

889
01:14:25,680 --> 01:14:31,680
But I think tech went through this journey of, 
oh, we're suddenly becoming important now, oh,  

890
01:14:31,680 --> 01:14:36,240
we're really, really important now, oh, we better 
stop playing this game of politics. And so I think  

891
01:14:36,240 --> 01:14:40,240
what I'm saying now is a lot more consensus 
than it was 10 years ago, but at the time,  

892
01:14:40,240 --> 01:14:44,480
the feeling was just like, "Look what we are doing 
is political, so you better engage with that."

893
01:14:44,480 --> 01:14:48,880
I think when this became really real for 
a lot of people is with the Ukraine War,  

894
01:14:48,880 --> 01:14:55,040
the government's running out of certain vehicles 
and ammunition, we're just not able to produce it,  

895
01:14:55,040 --> 01:14:58,800
and then we're like, "Oh, thank God for a company 
like Anduril and all these other tech companies  

896
01:14:58,800 --> 01:15:01,276
that are actually ahead and keeping us ahead." I 
think the only reason the US is ahead of that...

897
01:15:01,276 --> 01:15:04,800
And keeping us ahead. I think the only reason 
the US is ahead of China and the space race  

898
01:15:04,800 --> 01:15:08,240
is because SpaceX just is one company 
that just has been doing this for a long  

899
01:15:08,240 --> 01:15:13,040
time. So I think a lot of people have kind of 
realized, okay, maybe we need these things.

900
01:15:13,040 --> 01:15:18,480
Right. And I would make this argument as well, 
it's like people are like, well, how can you feel  

901
01:15:18,480 --> 01:15:22,240
good about working in defense? And it's like, 
well, you're not going to feel great if China  

902
01:15:22,240 --> 01:15:26,000
invades Taiwan, actually, you're not going 
to. I think you are probably also not going  

903
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:31,680
to like that outcome. So we do just live in this 
world where you do need to build up deterrents to  

904
01:15:31,680 --> 01:15:37,120
these things and they better be good. So to me, 
it didn't feel that difficult of a question. I  

905
01:15:37,120 --> 01:15:41,440
think when you zoom into particular things, they 
can be very difficult questions and there have  

906
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:46,640
been a bunch of those in the last couple of years. 
But yeah, again, disengagement isn't the answer.

907
01:15:46,640 --> 01:15:50,640
Yeah. And again, it's not for everyone. I think 
that's an important kind of theme through this  

908
01:15:50,640 --> 01:15:55,440
conversation is some companies ... like, to 
build ... sometimes to build a generational,  

909
